        <h1 class="doc-title">Formulas and Calculating Indefinite Integrals</h1>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Using Integration Formulas -->
    <h2>1. Using Integration Formulas</h2>
    <p>Calculating an indefinite integral means finding the complete family of antiderivatives of the integrand. If \(F'(x)=f(x)\), then</p>
    \[ \int f(x)\,dx=F(x)+C. \]

    <div class="t-box box-def">
        <div class="t-box-title">A RELIABLE PROCESS</div>
        <p>To calculate an indefinite integral:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>simplify or rewrite the integrand when necessary;</li>
            <li>separate sums and constant multiples;</li>
            <li>match each term to a known integration formula;</li>
            <li>include one constant of integration \(C\); and</li>
            <li>differentiate the answer to verify it.</li>
        </ol>
    </div>

    <p>Integration formulas reverse differentiation formulas. Pattern recognition is therefore essential: identify the function whose derivative produces the given integrand.</p>

    <!-- 2. Algebraic Formulas -->
    <h2>2. Algebraic Formulas</h2>

    <div class="t-box box-formula">
        <div class="t-box-title">CONSTANT AND POWER FORMULAS</div>
        <p>For a constant \(k\),</p>
        \[ \boxed{\int k\,dx=kx+C}. \]
        <p>For every real number \(n\neq -1\),</p>
        \[ \boxed{\int x^n\,dx=\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}+C}. \]
    </div>

    <p>The power formula means: increase the exponent by one, then divide by the new exponent. It is verified by</p>
    \[ \frac{d}{dx}\left(\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}\right)=x^n. \]

    <div class="t-box box-warning">
        <div class="t-box-title">WARNING // THE EXCEPTIONAL EXPONENT</div>
        <p>The power formula does not apply when \(n=-1\), because \(n+1=0\). Instead,</p>
        \[ \boxed{\int\frac{1}{x}\,dx=\ln|x|+C}. \]
        <p>The absolute value is necessary because the formula holds on intervals on either side of \(x=0\).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="t-box box-example">
        <div class="t-box-title">EXAMPLE 1: A NEGATIVE POWER</div>
        <p>Evaluate \(\int x^{-4}\,dx\).</p>
        \[
        \begin{aligned}
        \int x^{-4}\,dx &=\frac{x^{-3}}{-3}+C\\[3pt]
        &=\boxed{-\frac{1}{3x^3}+C}.
        \end{aligned}
        \]
        <p>Verification:</p>
        \[ \frac{d}{dx}\left(-\frac{1}{3}x^{-3}\right)=x^{-4}. \]
    </div>

    <!-- 3. Exponential Formulas -->
    <h2>3. Exponential Formulas</h2>
    <p>The exponential function \(e^x\) is its own derivative. Exponentials with other positive bases introduce a factor of \(\ln a\).</p>

    <div class="t-box box-formula">
        <div class="t-box-title">EXPONENTIAL INTEGRATION FORMULAS</div>
        \[ \boxed{\int e^x\,dx=e^x+C} \]
        <p>and, for \(a>0\) with \(a\neq 1\),</p>
        \[ \boxed{\int a^x\,dx=\frac{a^x}{\ln a}+C}. \]
    </div>

    <div class="t-box box-example">
        <div class="t-box-title">EXAMPLE 2: AN EXPONENTIAL FUNCTION</div>
        <p>Evaluate \(\int 5\cdot 2^x\,dx\).</p>
        \[
        \begin{aligned}
        \int 5\cdot 2^x\,dx &=5\int 2^x\,dx\\[3pt]
        &=\boxed{\frac{5\cdot 2^x}{\ln 2}+C}.
        \end{aligned}
        \]
    </div>

    <!-- 4. Trigonometric Formulas -->
    <h2>4. Trigonometric Formulas</h2>
    <p>The basic trigonometric integration formulas reverse familiar derivative rules.</p>

    <div class="t-box box-formula">
        <div class="t-box-title">BASIC TRIGONOMETRIC FORMULAS</div>
        \[
        \begin{aligned}
        \int\cos x\,dx&=\sin x+C,\\[3pt]
        \int\sin x\,dx&=-\cos x+C,\\[3pt]
        \int\sec^2x\,dx&=\tan x+C,\\[3pt]
        \int\csc^2x\,dx&=-\cot x+C,\\[3pt]
        \int\sec x\tan x\,dx&=\sec x+C,\\[3pt]
        \int\csc x\cot x\,dx&=-\csc x+C.
        \end{aligned}
        \]
    </div>

    <p>The negative signs in the sine, cosecant-squared, and cosecant-cotangent formulas come directly from the corresponding derivative formulas.</p>

    <div class="t-box box-example">
        <div class="t-box-title">EXAMPLE 3: A TRIGONOMETRIC COMBINATION</div>
        <p>Evaluate \[ \int\bigl(3\sec^2x+4\sin x-2\sec x\tan x\bigr)\,dx. \]</p>
        <p>Using linearity and the formula table,</p>
        \[
        \begin{aligned}
        &\int\bigl(3\sec^2x+4\sin x-2\sec x\tan x\bigr)\,dx\\[3pt]
        &\quad=3\tan x-4\cos x-2\sec x+C.
        \end{aligned}
        \]
        <p>Therefore, \[ \boxed{3\tan x-4\cos x-2\sec x+C}. \]</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 5. Rewriting Before Integrating -->
    <h2>5. Rewriting Before Integrating</h2>
    <p>Many integrands become straightforward after algebraic rewriting. Radicals should be written as fractional powers and reciprocal powers as negative exponents.</p>

    <div class="t-box box-example">
        <div class="t-box-title">EXAMPLE 4: RADICALS AND RECIPROCAL POWERS</div>
        <p>Evaluate \[ \int\left(4\sqrt{x}-\frac{3}{x^2}+\frac{2}{x}\right)\,dx. \]</p>
        <p>Rewrite the integrand:</p>
        \[ 4\sqrt{x}-\frac{3}{x^2}+\frac{2}{x} =4x^{1/2}-3x^{-2}+2x^{-1}. \]
        <p>Now integrate term by term:</p>
        \[
        \begin{aligned}
        &\int\left(4x^{1/2}-3x^{-2}+2x^{-1}\right)\,dx\\[3pt]
        &\quad=4\left(\frac{x^{3/2}}{3/2}\right) -3\left(\frac{x^{-1}}{-1}\right)+2\ln|x|+C\\[3pt]
        &\quad=\boxed{\frac{8}{3}x^{3/2}+\frac{3}{x}+2\ln|x|+C}.
        \end{aligned}
        \]
    </div>

    <div class="t-box box-example">
        <div class="t-box-title">EXAMPLE 5: DIVIDE BEFORE INTEGRATING</div>
        <p>Evaluate \[ \int\frac{x^3+2x^2-5}{x^2}\,dx. \]</p>
        <p>Divide each numerator term by \(x^2\):</p>
        \[ \frac{x^3+2x^2-5}{x^2}=x+2-5x^{-2}. \]
        <p>Thus,</p>
        \[
        \begin{aligned}
        \int\left(x+2-5x^{-2}\right)\,dx &=\frac{x^2}{2}+2x+5x^{-1}+C\\[3pt]
        &=\boxed{\frac{x^2}{2}+2x+\frac{5}{x}+C}.
        \end{aligned}
        \]
    </div>

    <!-- 6. Linear Inner Functions -->
    <h2>6. Linear Inner Functions</h2>
    <p>When an integrand contains \(ax+b\), differentiating the inner function produces the constant \(a\). Reversing the chain rule therefore introduces a factor of \(1/a\).</p>

    <div class="t-box box-formula">
        <div class="t-box-title">FORMULAS FOR A LINEAR INNER FUNCTION</div>
        <p>For \(a\neq 0\),</p>
        \[
        \begin{aligned}
        \int(ax+b)^n\,dx &=\frac{(ax+b)^{n+1}}{a(n+1)}+C, &&n\neq -1,\\[5pt]
        \int\frac{1}{ax+b}\,dx &=\frac{1}{a}\ln|ax+b|+C,\\[5pt]
        \int e^{ax+b}\,dx &=\frac{1}{a}e^{ax+b}+C,\\[5pt]
        \int\cos(ax+b)\,dx &=\frac{1}{a}\sin(ax+b)+C,\\[5pt]
        \int\sin(ax+b)\,dx &=-\frac{1}{a}\cos(ax+b)+C.
        \end{aligned}
        \]
    </div>

    <div class="t-box box-example">
        <div class="t-box-title">EXAMPLE 6: A POWER OF A LINEAR EXPRESSION</div>
        <p>Evaluate \(\int(3x-1)^4\,dx\).</p>
        \[
        \begin{aligned}
        \int(3x-1)^4\,dx &=\frac{(3x-1)^5}{3(5)}+C\\[3pt]
        &=\boxed{\frac{(3x-1)^5}{15}+C}.
        \end{aligned}
        \]
    </div>

    <div class="t-box box-example">
        <div class="t-box-title">EXAMPLE 7: LOGARITHMIC AND TRIGONOMETRIC FORMS</div>
        <p>Evaluate \[ \int\left(\frac{6}{2x+5}-4\sin(4x)\right)\,dx. \]</p>
        <p>Accounting for each inner derivative gives</p>
        \[
        \begin{aligned}
        \int\left(\frac{6}{2x+5}-4\sin(4x)\right)\,dx &=6\left(\frac12\ln|2x+5|\right) -4\left(-\frac14\cos(4x)\right)+C\\[3pt]
        &=\boxed{3\ln|2x+5|+\cos(4x)+C}.
        \end{aligned}
        \]
    </div>

    <!-- 7. Finding a Particular Antiderivative -->
    <h2>7. Finding a Particular Antiderivative</h2>
    <p>An initial condition selects one function from the family \(F(x)+C\).</p>

    <div class="t-box box-example">
        <div class="t-box-title">EXAMPLE 8: USING AN INITIAL CONDITION</div>
        <p>Find \(F\) if \[ F'(x)=3x^2-4 \qquad\text{and}\qquad F(1)=2. \]</p>
        <p>First find the general antiderivative: \[ F(x)=x^3-4x+C. \]</p>
        <p>Use the condition \(F(1)=2\): \[ 2=1^3-4(1)+C=-3+C, \]</p>
        <p>so \(C=5\). Therefore, \[ \boxed{F(x)=x^3-4x+5}. \]</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 8. Common Errors and Verification -->
    <h2>8. Common Errors and Verification</h2>
    
    <div class="t-box box-warning">
        <div class="t-box-title">WARNING // COMMON ERRORS</div>
        <ul>
            <li>Do not forget to divide by the new exponent in the power formula.</li>
            <li>Do not apply the power formula to \(x^{-1}\).</li>
            <li>Remember the negative sign in \(\int\sin x\,dx=-\cos x+C\).</li>
            <li>For \(ax+b\), account for the inner derivative by dividing by \(a\).</li>
            <li>Include one constant of integration \(C\) in the final answer.</li>
            <li>Simplify the integrand before deciding which formula to use.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <p>The final answer is correct if its derivative reproduces the original integrand. This check detects missing factors, incorrect exponents, and sign errors.</p>

    <!-- 9. Principal Results -->
    <h2>9. Principal Results</h2>
    
    <div class="t-box box-formula">
        <div class="t-box-title">CORE INTEGRATION FORMULAS</div>
        \[
        \begin{aligned}
        \int k\,dx&=kx+C,\\[3pt]
        \int x^n\,dx&=\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}+C, &&n\neq-1,\\[3pt]
        \int\frac1x\,dx&=\ln|x|+C,\\[3pt]
        \int e^x\,dx&=e^x+C,\\[3pt]
        \int a^x\,dx&=\frac{a^x}{\ln a}+C,\\[3pt]
        \int\cos x\,dx&=\sin x+C,\\[3pt]
        \int\sin x\,dx&=-\cos x+C,\\[3pt]
        \int\sec^2x\,dx&=\tan x+C,\\[3pt]
        \int\csc^2x\,dx&=-\cot x+C.
        \end{aligned}
        \]
    </div>

